    public override async Task SeedAsync()
    {
        // ── Overview (Article) ───────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Financial Reports Overview",
            Slug = "accounting-overview",
            Summary = "What the built-in Financial Reports are, the nine report pages, the standalone accounting boundary, and how reconciliation status is shown.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 6,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/accounting"]""",
            Tags = """["accounting","finance","reports"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Financial Reports Overview\n\nThe Accounting area is Forge's built-in financial reporting suite. It reads from the system's own general ledger (GL) and turns posted activity into the nine standard reports an office needs to read the health of the business: a Trial Balance, Profit & Loss, Balance Sheet, Cash Flow statement, AR and AP Aging, a GRNI (Goods Received Not Invoiced) report, a Period Close manager, and a Bank Reconciliation worksheet. Each report is read-only against the ledger — you are looking at what has already been posted, not editing transactions here.\n\n### ⚡ The Standalone Accounting Boundary\n\nThese reports are **standalone-mode features**. Forge can either run its own books or hand bookkeeping to an external accounting provider (QuickBooks, Xero, etc.). The two are mutually exclusive — the capability catalog declares `CAP-ACCT-EXTERNAL ⊥ CAP-ACCT-BUILTIN` as its one and only mutex pair. When an external provider is connected, the GL and these reports are dormant, because the provider is the source of truth for the books. When **no** external provider is connected, Forge runs in standalone mode and the built-in ledger activates. The whole Accounting area sits behind the `CAP-ACCT-FULLGL` route guard, so it stays hidden until the built-in suite is switched on. In short: these reports only do meaningful work in standalone mode, with the built-in GL turned on and no outside accounting system in the loop.\n\n### How You Get Around\n\nThe Accounting landing page is a grid of tiles — one per report — that route to the nine report pages plus a couple of supporting tools (Bank Statements import, Exports). Click a tile to open that report. Every report page opens with a standard page header (title + subtitle) and loads its data automatically when you arrive. Most reports also refresh themselves automatically whenever the underlying GL changes, so you rarely need to reload by hand.\n\n### The Nine Reports\n\n**Trial Balance** (`/accounting/trial-balance`) — A table of every GL account with its debit total, credit total, and net balance. A chip in the header reads **Balanced** (green) when total debits equal total credits, or **Out of Balance** (red) when they don't. A totals strip at the bottom sums the debit and credit columns. This is the foundation report — if the trial balance is out of balance, the other statements can't be trusted.\n\n**Profit & Loss** (`/accounting/profit-loss`) — An income statement laid out as Income lines, then Expense lines, each line showing its account number, account name, and amount. The report subtotals Total Income and Total Expense, then shows **Net Income** in the footer. If cost of goods sold hasn't been posted yet, a margin caveat note appears at the top so you read the margin with the right expectations.\n\n**Balance Sheet** (`/accounting/balance-sheet`) — Assets, Liabilities, and Equity sections, each line showing account number, name, and amount, with section subtotals. Equity includes a Current Year Earnings line. A header chip shows **Balanced** / **Out of Balance**, and the footer ties out Total Liabilities and Equity against Total Assets.\n\n**Cash Flow** (`/accounting/cash-flow`) — A statement of cash flows by the indirect method: it starts from Net Income, applies operating adjustments, then groups Investing and Financing activities, subtotaling net cash from each. The footer shows the Net Change in Cash and reconciles it against the Actual Cash Movement; a header chip reads **Reconciled** or **Out of Balance**.\n\n**AR Aging** (`/accounting/ar-aging`) — Accounts receivable aged into buckets (the standard ladder is 0-30 / 31-60 / 61-90 / 91+ days). Each customer is a row with an amount in each bucket plus an Open balance; a totals strip sums each bucket and the grand open total. A header chip reads **Ties to control** (the report ties to the AR control account) or **Out of Balance**.\n\n**AP Aging** (`/accounting/ap-aging`) — The mirror image for payables: each vendor aged across the same bucket ladder with an Open balance, a totals strip per bucket, and a **Ties to control** / **Out of Balance** chip against the AP control account.\n\n**GRNI** (`/accounting/grni`) — Goods Received Not Invoiced. It compares the GL balance of the GRNI clearing account against the operational open amount (goods physically received but not yet invoiced by the vendor) and shows the **Variance**. It then breaks the open amount down by purchase order across aging buckets and, when present, lists uncovered receipts that don't tie to an open PO line. A header chip reads **Reconciled** or **Variance**.\n\n**Period Close** (`/accounting/period-close`) — The fiscal-period manager. Fiscal years list their accounting periods; each period is **Open**, **Soft Closed**, or **Hard Closed**. You can soft-close a period (reversible — reopen later), hard-close it (locked), or close an entire year. Soft close blocks routine posting but can be reopened; hard close permanently locks the period.\n\n**Bank Reconciliation** (`/accounting/bank-rec`) — A worksheet that matches your book cash balance to a bank statement. You start a reconciliation by choosing a cash account, statement date, and ending balance; then you tick which ledger lines have cleared the bank. The worksheet shows Book Balance, Statement Ending Balance, the Cleared total, and the Outstanding total, and tells you the **Difference**. When the difference is zero the worksheet is **Reconciled** and can be **Finalized**.\n\n### Reading Reconciliation Status\n\nAlmost every report carries a status chip in its header that answers one question: *does this report tie out?* Green chips (Balanced, Reconciled, Ties to control) mean the report agrees with its control total. Red or amber chips (Out of Balance, Variance, Difference) mean something doesn't reconcile and needs investigation before you rely on the numbers. The chip is the fastest way to sanity-check a report at a glance.\n\n### When to Use Financial Reports\n\n- When you need a point-in-time read of the business — P&L for the period, Balance Sheet for the date\n- When confirming the books tie out — Trial Balance balanced, AR/AP aging tying to their control accounts\n- When chasing money — AR Aging for who owes you, AP Aging for what you owe\n- When closing a period — soft-close during review, hard-close to lock it down\n- When reconciling cash — matching the ledger to the bank statement on the Bank Rec worksheet\n- When investigating received-not-invoiced exposure — the GRNI variance and PO breakdown","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Walkthrough ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Financial Reports — Guided Tour",
            Slug = "accounting-walkthrough",
            Summary = "A guided tour of the Profit & Loss report and the shared report patterns: page header, statement layout, status chips, totals, and how the nine reports relate.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Walkthrough,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 2,
            AppRoutes = """["/accounting"]""",
            Tags = """["accounting","finance","reports","walkthrough"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"appRoute":"/accounting","startButtonLabel":"Tour Financial Reports","steps":[{"element":"app-page-header","popover":{"title":"The Accounting Hub","description":"This is the landing page for the built-in Financial Reports. Every report opens with a standard header like this one showing a title and subtitle, loads its data automatically when you arrive, and most refresh on their own whenever the underlying general ledger changes — you rarely need to reload by hand.","side":"bottom"}},{"element":".tile-grid","popover":{"title":"The Report Tiles","description":"The landing page is a grid of tiles — one per report — plus a couple of supporting tools (Bank Statements import, Exports). Click any tile to open that report. This grid is how you move between all nine reports and the tools without losing your place.","side":"top"}},{"element":".tile","popover":{"title":"Opening a Report","description":"Each tile routes to one report page: Trial Balance, Profit & Loss, Balance Sheet, Cash Flow, AR Aging, AP Aging, GRNI, Period Close, and Bank Reconciliation. Every report is read-only against the posted ledger — you are looking at what has already posted, not editing transactions here.","side":"right"}},{"element":".tile-grid","popover":{"title":"Statement vs Table Reports","description":"Profit & Loss, Balance Sheet, and Cash Flow render as a 'statement' grouped into sections (Income/Expense, Assets/Liabilities/Equity, Operating/Investing/Financing) with subtotals and a headline footer figure like Net Income. The aging reports, Trial Balance, Period Close, and Bank Rec render as a sortable, filterable data table with a totals strip and the aging bucket ladder (0-30 / 31-60 / 61-90 / 91+).","side":"bottom"}},{"element":"app-page-header","popover":{"title":"Status Chips","description":"Most reports add a status chip to their header that answers one question: does the report tie out? Trial Balance and Balance Sheet show Balanced / Out of Balance. Cash Flow and GRNI show Reconciled / Variance. AR and AP Aging show 'Ties to control' when they agree with their control account. Green means it reconciles; red or amber means investigate.","side":"bottom"}},{"element":".page-content","popover":{"title":"Where to Start","description":"Start with the Trial Balance to confirm the books tie out, then read the Profit & Loss for the period and the Balance Sheet for the date. Use AR and AP Aging to chase money, GRNI for received-not-invoiced exposure, Period Close to lock a period, and Bank Reconciliation to match the ledger to a bank statement. Pick any tile above to dive in.","side":"top"}}]}"""
        });

        // ── Field Reference (QuickRef) ───────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Financial Reports Field Reference",
            Slug = "accounting-field-reference",
            Summary = "Reference for every financial report: the columns, lines, status chips, totals, and actions on each of the nine report pages.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.QuickRef,
            EstimatedMinutes = 6,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 3,
            AppRoutes = """["/accounting"]""",
            Tags = """["accounting","finance","reports","reference"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"title":"Financial Reports Field Reference","groups":[{"heading":"The Standalone Accounting Boundary","items":[{"label":"Standalone mode","value":"The built-in Financial Reports are standalone-mode features. They run off Forge's own general ledger and are meaningful only when NO external accounting provider (QuickBooks, Xero, etc.) is connected."},{"label":"Mutex pair","value":"The capability catalog declares CAP-ACCT-EXTERNAL ⊥ CAP-ACCT-BUILTIN — built-in books and an external provider are mutually exclusive. Connecting a provider makes the GL and these reports dormant."},{"label":"Route guard","value":"The whole Accounting area sits behind the CAP-ACCT-FULLGL route guard, so it stays hidden until the built-in suite is switched on."},{"label":"Read-only","value":"Every report reads from the posted ledger — you view what has already posted; you do not edit transactions on these pages (Period Close and Bank Rec are the only pages with actions)."},{"label":"Status chip","value":"Most reports carry a header chip answering 'does this tie out?' Green (Balanced / Reconciled / Ties to control) = agrees with its control total. Red or amber (Out of Balance / Variance / Difference) = investigate before relying on the numbers."}]},{"heading":"AP Aging (/accounting/ap-aging)","items":[{"label":"Purpose","value":"Accounts payable aged by how long bills have been outstanding — what you owe vendors, grouped by age."},{"label":"Rows","value":"One row per vendor (party name), with an amount in each aging bucket plus an Open balance. First column is sticky during horizontal scroll."},{"label":"Aging buckets","value":"The standard ladder is 0-30 / 31-60 / 61-90 / 91+ days, rendered as columns b0..b5 (the table supports up to six buckets; bucket labels come from the report). Each is sortable, right-aligned, currency."},{"label":"Totals strip","value":"Bottom strip sums each bucket and shows the grand Open total."},{"label":"Status chip","value":"'Ties to control' (green) when the report ties to the AP control account, or 'Out of Balance' (red)."}]},{"heading":"AR Aging (/accounting/ar-aging)","items":[{"label":"Purpose","value":"Accounts receivable aged by how long invoices have been outstanding — who owes you, grouped by age."},{"label":"Rows","value":"One row per customer (party name), with an amount in each aging bucket plus an Open balance. First column is sticky during horizontal scroll."},{"label":"Aging buckets","value":"Same 0-30 / 31-60 / 61-90 / 91+ ladder as AP, columns b0..b5, sortable and currency-formatted; labels come from the report's bucket set."},{"label":"Totals strip","value":"Bottom strip sums each bucket and shows the grand Open total."},{"label":"Status chip","value":"'Ties to control' (green) when the report ties to the AR control account, or 'Out of Balance' (red)."}]},{"heading":"Balance Sheet (/accounting/balance-sheet)","items":[{"label":"Purpose","value":"Point-in-time statement of financial position: Assets, Liabilities, Equity."},{"label":"Sections","value":"Assets, Liabilities, and Equity — each line shows account number, account name, and amount, with a section subtotal (Total Assets, Total Liabilities, Total Equity)."},{"label":"Current Year Earnings","value":"An explicit equity line; Total Equity is shown with current-year earnings folded in (Total Equity With Earnings)."},{"label":"Footer","value":"Total Liabilities And Equity — ties out against Total Assets when the sheet is balanced."},{"label":"Status chip","value":"'Balanced' (green) when assets equal liabilities plus equity, or 'Out of Balance' (red)."}]},{"heading":"Bank Reconciliation (/accounting/bank-rec)","items":[{"label":"Purpose","value":"Matches the book cash balance to a bank statement by marking which ledger lines have cleared the bank."},{"label":"Start form","value":"Cash Account (required select), Statement Date (required), and Ending Balance (currency) — then click Start to open a worksheet."},{"label":"Summary table","value":"Book Balance, Statement Ending Balance, Cleared total, and Outstanding total."},{"label":"Cleared checkbox","value":"Per-line checkbox marks an entry cleared. Ticking only STAGES the change — nothing persists until you click 'Update cleared'. The unsaved-count is shown next to the button (no autosave)."},{"label":"Difference","value":"Header chip shows 'Reconciled' (green) when the difference is zero, otherwise the 'Difference' amount (amber)."},{"label":"Status / Finalize","value":"Worksheet status is Draft or Finalized. Finalize is enabled only when reconciled and there are no unsaved cleared changes. A list of prior reconciliations is shown when no worksheet is open; click a row to reopen it."}]},{"heading":"Cash Flow (/accounting/cash-flow)","items":[{"label":"Purpose","value":"Statement of cash flows, indirect method — how cash moved across operating, investing, and financing activities."},{"label":"Operating","value":"Starts from Net Income, applies operating adjustment lines, subtotals Net Cash From Operating."},{"label":"Investing","value":"Shown only when investing lines exist; subtotals Net Cash From Investing."},{"label":"Financing","value":"Financing lines, subtotaling Net Cash From Financing (shows a 'none' placeholder when empty)."},{"label":"Footer","value":"Net Change In Cash, then a reconcile row showing Actual Cash Movement."},{"label":"Status chip","value":"'Reconciled' (green) when the computed net change matches actual cash movement, or 'Out of Balance' (red)."}]},{"heading":"GRNI — Goods Received Not Invoiced (/accounting/grni)","items":[{"label":"Purpose","value":"Reconciles the GRNI clearing account: goods physically received but not yet invoiced by the vendor."},{"label":"Summary","value":"GL Balance (clearing account), Operational Open (received-not-invoiced per operations), and the Variance between them."},{"label":"Open by Purchase Order","value":"Breaks the open amount down by PO across aging buckets (b0..b5) with an Open Amount per row; first column sticky. A totals strip sums each bucket and the grand Open total."},{"label":"Uncovered receipts","value":"When present, lists receipts that don't tie to an open PO line; the heading shows a count (with a '+' when truncated). Receipt number falls back to an em dash when blank."},{"label":"Status chip","value":"'Reconciled' (green) when GL balance equals operational open, otherwise 'Variance'."}]},{"heading":"Period Close (/accounting/period-close)","items":[{"label":"Purpose","value":"Manages fiscal years and their accounting periods — controls what can still be posted."},{"label":"Fiscal year","value":"Each year shows a name and an Open/Closed chip; an open year has a 'Close Year' action."},{"label":"Periods","value":"Each year lists its periods with a date range (start – end) and a status chip."},{"label":"Period statuses","value":"Open (green) = posting allowed. Soft Closed (amber) = routine posting blocked but reversible. Hard Closed (muted) = permanently locked."},{"label":"Period actions","value":"From Open: Soft Close or Hard Close. From Soft Closed: Reopen or Hard Close. Hard Closed shows 'Locked' with no further actions. Buttons disable while a close/reopen is in flight."}]},{"heading":"Profit & Loss (/accounting/profit-loss)","items":[{"label":"Purpose","value":"Income statement for the period — revenue, expenses, and the resulting net income."},{"label":"Income lines","value":"Each income line shows account number, account name, and amount; subtotaled as Total Income ('No income' placeholder when empty)."},{"label":"Expense lines","value":"Each expense line shows account number, account name, and amount; subtotaled as Total Expense ('No expense' placeholder when empty)."},{"label":"Net Income","value":"Footer figure: Total Income minus Total Expense."},{"label":"Margin caveat","value":"When COGS has not been posted, a caveat note appears at the top warning that the margin is incomplete. Absent once COGS is posted."}]},{"heading":"Trial Balance (/accounting/trial-balance)","items":[{"label":"Purpose","value":"Lists every GL account with its debit total, credit total, and net balance — the foundation report for all the statements."},{"label":"Columns","value":"Account Number, Account, Debit, Credit, Net — Debit/Credit/Net are sortable, right-aligned, currency."},{"label":"Totals strip","value":"Bottom strip shows Total Debit and Total Credit; they are equal when the books balance."},{"label":"Status chip","value":"'Balanced' (green) when total debits equal total credits, or 'Out of Balance' (red). If the trial balance is out of balance, the other statements can't be trusted."}]},{"heading":"Shared Patterns","items":[{"label":"Auto-refresh","value":"Most reports refresh automatically when the underlying GL changes — no manual reload needed."},{"label":"Statement vs table","value":"P&L, Balance Sheet, Cash Flow, and GRNI summary render as 'statement'/'summary' tables. Trial Balance, AR/AP Aging, GRNI PO breakdown, Period Close, and Bank Rec render in the shared data table (sortable columns, per-column filters)."},{"label":"Default book","value":"Reports query a single default accounting book today (book id 1); a book selector arrives with multi-book support."},{"label":"Landing tiles","value":"The Accounting landing page is a grid of tiles routing to each report plus supporting tools (Bank Statements import, Exports)."}]}]}"""
        });

        // ── Knowledge Check (Quiz) ───────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Financial Reports Knowledge Check",
            Slug = "accounting-quiz",
            Summary = "Test your knowledge of the built-in Financial Reports: the accounting boundary, status chips, aging buckets, period close, and bank reconciliation.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Quiz,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 4,
            AppRoutes = """["/accounting"]""",
            Tags = """["accounting","finance","reports","quiz"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"passingScore":80,"questionsPerQuiz":8,"shuffleOptions":true,"showExplanationsAfterSubmit":true,"questions":[{"id":"ac1","text":"When do the built-in Financial Reports actually do meaningful work?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Whenever an external accounting provider like QuickBooks is connected"},{"id":"b","text":"In standalone mode — when NO external accounting provider is connected and the built-in general ledger is switched on","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Only after every fiscal period has been hard-closed"},{"id":"d","text":"Only when both an external provider AND the built-in ledger are enabled at the same time"}],"explanation":"These are standalone-mode features. The capability catalog declares CAP-ACCT-EXTERNAL ⊥ CAP-ACCT-BUILTIN as a mutex — built-in books and an external provider are mutually exclusive. When a provider is connected the GL and these reports are dormant; they run off Forge's own ledger only in standalone mode, behind the CAP-ACCT-FULLGL guard."},{"id":"ac2","text":"The Trial Balance header shows a red 'Out of Balance' chip. What does that tell you?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The report failed to load and should be refreshed"},{"id":"b","text":"Total debits do not equal total credits, so the other statements can't be trusted until it's fixed","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"A fiscal period needs to be hard-closed before the report will balance"},{"id":"d","text":"There are uncovered receipts that don't tie to a purchase order"}],"explanation":"The Trial Balance chip reads 'Balanced' (green) when total debits equal total credits and 'Out of Balance' (red) when they don't. It's the foundation report — if the trial balance is out of balance, the P&L, Balance Sheet, and Cash Flow built on top of it can't be relied on."},{"id":"ac3","text":"What is the standard aging bucket ladder used by the AR Aging and AP Aging reports?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"0-7 / 8-14 / 15-30 / 31+ days"},{"id":"b","text":"Current / Past Due / Written Off"},{"id":"c","text":"0-30 / 31-60 / 61-90 / 91+ days","isCorrect":true},{"id":"d","text":"Monthly columns for the trailing twelve months"}],"explanation":"Both aging reports use the standard 0-30 / 31-60 / 61-90 / 91+ day ladder, rendered as bucket columns with an Open balance per party. The totals strip sums each bucket and the grand open total."},{"id":"ac4","text":"On the Profit & Loss report, what does the margin caveat note at the top mean?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The report is out of balance"},{"id":"b","text":"Cost of goods sold hasn't been posted yet, so the margin you're reading is incomplete","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"An external accounting provider is connected and the P&L is read-only"},{"id":"d","text":"The fiscal period is hard-closed and the figures are final"}],"explanation":"When COGS hasn't been posted, the P&L shows a caveat note so you read Net Income with the right expectations — the margin is incomplete until COGS lands. Once COGS is posted, the note disappears."},{"id":"ac5","text":"In Period Close, what is the difference between a Soft Closed and a Hard Closed period?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"They are the same — both permanently lock the period"},{"id":"b","text":"Soft Closed blocks routine posting but can be reopened; Hard Closed permanently locks the period","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Soft Closed locks the period; Hard Closed only warns when posting"},{"id":"d","text":"Soft Closed applies to a period; Hard Closed applies to an entire fiscal year"}],"explanation":"A Soft Closed period (amber chip) blocks routine posting but is reversible — you can Reopen it. A Hard Closed period (muted chip) is permanently locked and shows 'Locked' with no further actions. From an Open period you can soft- or hard-close; from Soft Closed you can reopen or hard-close."},{"id":"ac6","text":"On the Bank Reconciliation worksheet, you tick several lines as cleared. What happens?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Each tick saves immediately to the ledger"},{"id":"b","text":"Ticking only stages the change — nothing persists until you click 'Update cleared'","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The worksheet finalizes automatically once any line is cleared"},{"id":"d","text":"The lines are deleted from the reconciliation"}],"explanation":"Cleared is a transient client-side selection consistent with the app's button-driven, no-autosave model. Ticking stages the change and shows an unsaved-count; nothing persists until you click 'Update cleared'. Finalize is only enabled when the worksheet is reconciled and there are no unsaved cleared changes."},{"id":"ac7","text":"The GRNI report shows a non-zero Variance. What is it comparing?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Total debits against total credits across the whole ledger"},{"id":"b","text":"The GL balance of the GRNI clearing account against the operational open amount (goods received but not yet invoiced)","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Book cash balance against the bank statement ending balance"},{"id":"d","text":"Total Assets against Total Liabilities and Equity"}],"explanation":"GRNI (Goods Received Not Invoiced) reconciles the clearing account: it compares the GL Balance against the Operational Open amount and reports the Variance. A 'Reconciled' chip means they agree; a 'Variance' chip means they don't. The report also breaks the open amount down by purchase order and flags uncovered receipts."},{"id":"ac8","text":"You need to see which customers owe you money and how overdue each balance is. Which report do you open?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"AP Aging"},{"id":"b","text":"AR Aging","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Cash Flow"},{"id":"d","text":"Trial Balance"}],"explanation":"AR Aging (accounts receivable) shows who owes you, with each customer's open balance spread across the 0-30 / 31-60 / 61-90 / 91+ aging buckets. AP Aging is the mirror image for what you owe vendors. Cash Flow and Trial Balance don't break balances down by party."}]}"""
        });

        Log.Information("Seeded Accounting training modules");
    }
}
